title: For Sale:  Pre WW2 22 Cal Mauser "ERMA" Training Rifle
postcontent: This 22 Mauser Training Rifle is made by ERMA in Erfurt Germany. This model was made in the early 1930's and used thru WW2 to train Mid and High School Youth in the Basic shooting skills. This early training was to ensure students were to be ready to be inducted into the NAZI military. These rifles were issued all over pre-war Germany to schools and various Target Shooting Clubs. Just another way to get around the WW1 Surrender terms. These high quality rifles made by many contractors such as this one by ERMA. This Rifle is an extremely very rare rifle as not only does it have ALL MATCHING NUMBERS of Barrel, Action and of all things, even the original BOLT matches TOO! Even with the forend of the stock cut off at the front band this is a very hard to find rifle. this last was probably done when issued to the elderly or the Hitler youth in the closing days of the war. This is an extremely accurate rifle and could be an excellent choice as a youth training rifle with a possible shot to getting a rabbit or squirrel for the Pot. The starting price on this is low as it has been in my closet for a long time and my son has acquired his own collection. I highly recommend westernunion but will also accept payment by USPS Money Order, and cash deposit with shipment. I a dealer and as a collector no returns or refunds will be accepted. Only exception, if I have misidentified the items manufacture or contract country. No "Wife changed my mind for me" problems. shipping for this rifle as it is a lightweight will be $35. paid with the purchase amount. This rifle is C&R eligible so either a current C&R FFL or a Dealer FFL will suffice.

title: For Sale:  1893 Swiss Mannlicher Carbine SIG in 7.5X53.5 Swiss 1893 Cavalry Carbine Very RARE PRICE DROP
postcontent: This VERY RARE Swiss 1893 Mannlicher Cavalry Carbine in Excellent Condition which makes this exceptionally RARE. This is chambered for the Swiss GP-90 which is 7.5X53.5 and the brass is easily trimmed from the 7.5X55 Swiss. This is one of less than 7000 total produced. Nearly 3500 made by SIG-Neuhausen in 1895, the remainder by Waffenfabrik Bern. Which also attributes to it's rarity. Very few remain as they were well used by the Cavalry they were issued to. This beautiful rifle does not show much evidence of more than very little carry wear and almost no firing as the bolt head has only a very faint primer ring. Every Serial Number on this Rare Carbine matches even the inside of the stock. Shows beautifully grained and tiger-striped wood the length of the stock. Well over 85% original bluing with small areas of bluing worn at receiver bridge, sides of both bands and bottom of trigger guard. There are no metal surfaces heavily marred or scratched.
